ğŸ”¹ What is a Class in C++?
A class in C++ is a blueprint (like a plan or design) for creating objects.

ğŸ“Œ Think of it like a "cookie cutter" ğŸª:

The class is the cookie cutter (the design).
The objects are the actual cookies (real things created from the design).
ğŸ’¡ Example:

class Car {
    // Class body (blueprint)
};
This doesn't do anything yet, but it defines what a "Car" is.

ğŸ”¹ Objects: The Real Things from a Class
An object is a real instance of a class.

ğŸ“Œ Example:

class Car {
public:
    string brand;
};

int main() {
    Car myCar;  // Creating an object from the Car class
    myCar.brand = "Toyota";
    cout << myCar.brand << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:
Toyota

ğŸš€ Here, myCar is an object of class Car!

ğŸ”¹ Defining a Class in C++
A class contains attributes (data) and methods (functions).

ğŸ“Œ Example: A Class with Attributes and Methods

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Dog {
public:  
    string name;
    int age;

    void bark() {
        cout << name << " says Woof Woof!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Dog myDog;
    myDog.name = "Buddy";
    myDog.age = 3;
    
    cout << myDog.name << " is " << myDog.age << " years old." << endl;
    myDog.bark();

    return 0;
}

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Buddy is 3 years old.
Buddy says Woof Woof!

ğŸ”¹ Class Members (Attributes & Methods)
A class contains:
Type + What it is? + Example
Attributes + Variables inside a class +	string color;
Methods + Functions inside a class + void drive() { cout << "Vroom!"; }
ğŸ“Œ Example:

class Car {
public:
    string brand;  // Attribute
    void honk() {  // Method
        cout << "Beep Beep!" << endl;
    }
};
ğŸ”¹ Private vs Public Members
In C++, class members can be:

Access Specifier	Who Can Access It?	Example
public	Everyone can access	public: int speed;
private	Only inside the class	private: int engineNumber;
ğŸ“Œ Example:

class BankAccount {
private:
    double balance;  // Private variable

public:
    void setBalance(double b) {  // Public method
        balance = b;
    }
    double getBalance() {  // Public method
        return balance;
    }
};

int main() {
    BankAccount myAccount;
    myAccount.setBalance(1000);
    cout << "Balance: $" << myAccount.getBalance() << endl;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:


Balance: $1000
ğŸš€ Private members (balance) can't be accessed directly! They need methods.

ğŸ”¹ Constructors: Automatic Setup for Objects
A constructor is a special function that runs automatically when you create an object.

ğŸ“Œ Example:


class Car {
public:
    string brand;

    // Constructor (same name as class)
    Car(string b) {
        brand = b;
    }

    void showBrand() {
        cout << "This car is a " << brand << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Car myCar("Tesla");  // Constructor runs automatically
    myCar.showBrand();

    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:


This car is a Tesla
ğŸš€ Constructors make initialization easier!

ğŸ”¹ Destructors: Cleanup When Objects are Deleted
A destructor is a function that runs when an object is destroyed.

ğŸ“Œ Example:


class Car {
public:
    Car() {  // Constructor
        cout << "Car is created!" << endl;
    }

    ~Car() {  // Destructor
        cout << "Car is destroyed!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Car myCar;
    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:


Car is created!
Car is destroyed!
ğŸš€ Destructors clean up resources when objects are deleted.

ğŸ”¹ Inheritance: One Class from Another
Inheritance allows a new class to reuse the code of an existing class.

ğŸ“Œ Example:


class Animal {
public:
    void eat() {
        cout << "I can eat!" << endl;
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {  // Dog inherits from Animal
public:
    void bark() {
        cout << "Woof Woof!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Dog myDog;
    myDog.eat();  // Inherited from Animal
    myDog.bark(); // Own method

    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:


I can eat!
Woof Woof!
ğŸš€ Dog inherits from Animal, so it can eat too!

ğŸ”¹ Polymorphism: One Function, Different Forms
Polymorphism lets a function behave differently for different objects.

ğŸ“Œ Example:

class Animal {
public:
    virtual void sound() {
        cout << "Animal makes a sound" << endl;
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void sound() override {
        cout << "Dog barks" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Animal* a;
    Dog d;
    a = &d;
    a->sound();  // Calls Dog's sound

    return 0;
}
ğŸ”¹ Output:

Dog barks
ğŸš€ Virtual functions allow dynamic behavior!

ğŸ”¹ Summary of Classes in C++
âœ” A class is a blueprint for objects.
âœ” An object is an instance of a class.
âœ” Access Specifiers control who can access what.
âœ” Constructors initialize objects automatically.
âœ” Destructors clean up when objects are deleted.
âœ” Inheritance allows code reuse between classes.
âœ” Polymorphism lets functions behave differently.

